"Hourcade J.-C., Chapuis T.","No-regret potentials and technical innovation. A viability approach to integrated assessment of climate policies",1995,"Energy Policy","23","4-5",,"433","445",,,10.1016/0301-4215(95)90168-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0029486495&partnerID=40&md5=868221ece22ce765587699ceae261a0b","Centre International de Recherche sur l'Environnement et le Développement (CIRED-CNRS), 1 rue du, 11 Novembre, 92120 Montrouge, France","Hourcade, J.-C., Centre International de Recherche sur l'Environnement et le Développement (CIRED-CNRS), 1 rue du, 11 Novembre, 92120 Montrouge, France; Chapuis, T., Centre International de Recherche sur l'Environnement et le Développement (CIRED-CNRS), 1 rue du, 11 Novembre, 92120 Montrouge, France","This paper aims to demonstrate the advantages of a sequential approach to decision making in climate policies. This sequential approach is necessary because of the uncertainties regarding both the avoided costs of climate change and the costs of GHG emission abatement. This assessment focuses on the minimization of learning time, the reduction of technical and institutional inertia, and the possible unexpected non-linearities in abatement curves. A stylized representation of so-called 'no-regret' short-term potentials, of long-term innovation trends and of backstop technologies is used. We show that if we do take care of the inertia constraints in the decision process, both policies (namely the no-regret and the innovation process exploitation) becomes crucial in terms of minimization of the learning time. © 1995.","Global warming; No-regret policies; Technological development","climate change model; climate change policy; climatic change; decision making; economic evaluation; environmental economics; global warming; global warming policy; integrated assessment; integrated assessment model; no-regret policy; sequential approach decision; technological development; viability approach",,,,,,"Allais, Le comportement de l'homme rationnel devant le risque (1953) Critique des postulats de l'école américaine, 21, pp. 503-546. , Econometrica; Chichilnisky, Heal, International emission permits: equity and efficiency (1993) Working Paper, , Columbia Business School, New York; Cline, (1992) The Economics of Global Warming, , Institute for International Economics, Washington DC; Dean, Cost of Cutting CO2 Emissions: Evidence from Top-Down Model? (1993) International Conference on the Economics of Climate Change, , OECD, Paris; Fankhauser, Pearce, The Social Cost of Reducing CO2 Emissions (1992) OECD/AIE Conference; Goulder, 50th Congress of the International Institute of Public Finance (1994) Environmental taxation and the double dividend a reader's guide, , 22–24 August; Grubb, Sebenius, (1991) Participation, Allocation, and Adaptability in International Tradeable Emission Permit Systems for Greenhouse Gas Control, , OECD, Paris; Henry, Investment projects and natural resources: economic rationality of Janus (1989) Ecological Economics, 1, pp. 117-135; Hoel, Efficient climate policy in the presence of free rider (1993) Journal of Environmental Economics and Management; Hourcade, Economic issues and negotiation on the global environment: some lessons from the recent experience on the greenhouse effect (1993) Trade, Innovation, Environment, , C Carraro, Kluwer, Dordrecht; Hourcade, Salles, Théry, Land use regulation in the Lake Georgia Basin: an ecological economic perspective (1992) Ecological Economics, 6 (3), pp. 211-233; Lave, Formulating greenhouse policies in a sea of uncertainty (1991) The Energy Journal, 12 (1), pp. 9-21; Manne, Richels, (1992) Buying Greenhouse Insurance: The Economic Costs of CO2, , MIT Press, Cambridge, MA; Manne, Richels, The Cost of Stabilizing Global CO2 Emissions: A Probabilistic Analysis Based on Expert Judgments (1994) Energy Journal, 15 (1), pp. 31-56; Mégie, Modélisation prospective, critères de décision et négotiation internationale d'un dévelo